        <body>
            <list type="ontology" xml:id="myOntology">
                <head>Abesabesi Categories</head>
                <item xml:id="noun">
                    <term>Noun</term>
                    <gloss> The noun is a word class that refer to a broad range of entities or
                        experiences in the world. In contrast to verbs, they start with a vowel. </gloss>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="noun-classification">
                            <term>Classification </term>
                            <gloss> Nominal classification is a phenomenon in some languages, where
                                nouns are grouped in noun classes according to semantic traits. Noun
                                classes can be morphologically marked. </gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="noun-functionNoun">
                            <term>Function Noun</term>
                            <gloss> Function nouns are a subclass of nouns. They express a
                                grammatical or semantic relation towards another constituent of the
                                clause and are thus semantically similar to prepositions. </gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="noun-property">
                            <term>Property Noun</term>
                            <gloss> Property nouns are a subclass of nouns. They express a
                                property and can be used alone or as nominal modifiers. </gloss>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="allomorph">
                    <term>Allomorph</term>
                    <gloss> Allomorphs are considered to be alternative representations of a
                        Morpheme. </gloss>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="agreement">
                    <term>Agreement</term>
                    <gloss> A word agrees with another word, when it changes form to take on the same value of the other word's grammatical 
                        category. </gloss>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="languages">
                    <term>Languages</term>
                    <gloss> other languages than Abesabesi </gloss>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="languages-ukaan">
                            <term>Ukaan</term>
                            <gloss> Ukaan is a surrounding language. </gloss>
                            <list>
                                <item xml:id="languages-ukaan-ikaan">
                                    <term>Ikaan</term>
                                    <gloss>Ikaan is a dialect of Ukaan</gloss>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="languages-akokoid">
                            <term>Akokoid</term>
                            <gloss> Akokoid is a surrounding language. </gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="languages-ayereahan">
                            <term>Ayere-Ahan</term>
                            <gloss> Ayere and Ahan are two surrounding languages. </gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="languages-yoruba">
                            <term>Yoruba</term>
                            <gloss> Yoruba is a surrounding language and the lingua franca of the
                                south west of Nigeria. </gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="languages-edoid">
                            <term>Edoid</term>
                            <gloss> Edoid is a language family present in the Akoko region. </gloss>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="akoko">
                    <term>Akoko</term>
                    <gloss> Akoko is a region in the north of Ondo state, Nigeria. </gloss>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="vowel">
                    <term>Vowel</term>
                    <gloss>Vowels are segmental phonemes that involve an underhindered stream of
                        air</gloss>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="vowel-atr">
                            <term>Advanced Tongue Root</term>
                            <gloss> Advanced Tongue Root (ATR) is a feature on vowels. </gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="vowel-harmony">
                            <term>Harmony</term>
                            <gloss> Vowel harmony is is a special type of assimilation, where vowels
                                are classified into two or more groups based on specific features
                                and words usually consist of only vowels of one of those groups.
                                Vowels in affixes then assimilate to the root vowels' group in order
                                to fit into that group. </gloss>
                            <list>
                                <item xml:id="vowel-harmony-prefix">
                                    <term>Prefix</term>
                                    <gloss>Prefix vowel harmony is a type of vowel harmony in
                                        Abesabesi that only applies to prefixes, such as bound
                                        subject pronouns and tam morphemes.</gloss>
                                </item>
                                <item xml:id="vowel-harmony-suffix">
                                    <term>Suffix</term>
                                    <gloss>Suffix vowel harmony is a type of vowel harmony in
                                        Abesabesi that only applies to prefixes, such as bound
                                        object/possessive pronouns, the pluractionalis extension or
                                        the gerund suffix.</gloss>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="vowel-quality">
                            <term>Quality</term>
                            <gloss>Vowel quality in Abesabesi is defined by the tongue position,
                                lowness, roundedness and the ATR value.</gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="vowel-nasality">
                            <term>Nasality</term>
                            <gloss>A nasal vowel is produced when the velum is lowered so that parts
                                of the airstream escapes through the nasal cavity.</gloss>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="pronoun">
                    <term>Pronoun</term>
                    <gloss>A pronoun is a word that replaces a noun</gloss>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="pronoun-independent">
                            <term>Independent Pronoun</term>
                            <gloss>Independent Pronouns are a class of pronouns that are independent and generally used
                            to express emphasis.</gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="pronoun-emphatic">
                            <term>Emphatic Pronoun</term>
                            <gloss> An emphatic pronoun is a specific type of personal pronoun. They are
                                used in similar context than independent pronouns, but put an emphasis on
                                the referenced person. </gloss>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </item>
                
                <item xml:id="verb">
                    <term>Verb</term>
                    <gloss> A verb is... </gloss>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="verb-defunct">
                            <term>Defunct Verb</term>
                            <gloss> The subclass of defunct verbs encompasses three verbs: té 'exist', gó 'it is', and síkɔ́ 'where is/what about'. </gloss>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="focus">
                    <term>Focus</term>
                    <gloss/>
                    <list>
                        <item xml:id="focus-construction">
                            <term>Focus construction</term>
                            <gloss>A focus construction is a specific type of clause, where one constituent is fronted to express
                                focus.</gloss>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="focus-contrastive">
                            <term>Contrastive focus</term>
                            <gloss>Contrastive focus is a way to mark that the proposition of a clause is contrary to the presupposition of the interlocutor.</gloss>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                    
                </item>              
                <item xml:id="emphasis">
                    <term>Emphasis</term>
                    <gloss>Emphasis is a functional category that can be attributed to a form.</gloss>
                </item>
                <item xml:id="clause">
                    <term>Clause</term>
                    <gloss>A clause is a syntactic unit that minimally contains a subject and a predicate.</gloss>
                </item>
            </list>
        </body>
